### BUG 3 — `find` is not tree-aware [CRITICAL]

`execute.rs:998–1068`

`cmd_find_global` calls `list_categories()` (top-level dirs only) then `list_documents(cat)` per category (direct files only). It never descends into subdirectories. Any file or dir at depth > 1 is completely invisible to `find`.

`cmd_find_scoped` (`-c DIR`) calls `list_documents(dir)` — same problem: no recursion.

Fix: `find` must recursively walk the tree using `list_directory` at each node, or the server must expose a recursive search/find RPC endpoint.

---

### BUG 4 — shell completion is category-era throughout [SERIOUS]

`shell.rs:101–127`

`ensure_categories()` calls `list_categories()` → only top-level dirs in cache.
`ensure_docs(cat)` calls `list_documents(cat)` → only direct files per dir.
`complete_path()` knows only `cat/doc` structure — no depth, no nested dirs.

Consequences:
- Tab completion for `mv src <TAB>` as destination: only shows top-level dirs, never subdirs → the Enginseer's autocomplete bug
- Tab completion for any command (`cat`, `put`, `append`, `head`, `tail`, etc.) fails for paths at depth > 1
- `ls <TAB>` only offers top-level dirs, not subdirs

